00:04:29.700 --> 00:04:35.340
Okay. Cuba and Angola share a long
history of Iberian colonization,

00:04:35.340 --> 00:04:37.440
dating from the 15th century.

00:04:37.440 --> 00:04:40.150
And are also two poles of the
trans-Atlantic slave trade

00:04:40.150 --> 00:04:42.410
that continued into the 19th.

00:04:42.410 --> 00:04:44.190
More recently, they
shared the histories

00:04:44.190 --> 00:04:46.820 position:56%
of 20th century leftist revolutions.

00:04:46.820 --> 00:04:49.520
Cuba's, of course,
triumphed in 1959,

00:04:49.520 --> 00:04:54.260
while Angola won its
independence from Portugal in 1975.

00:04:54.260 --> 00:04:58.620
In both places, the link between
the colonial past and the threat

00:04:58.620 --> 00:05:03.210
of a neo-colonial present provided
an on-going rhetorical basis

00:05:03.210 --> 00:05:05.610
for seeing Cuba and
Angola as involved

00:05:05.610 --> 00:05:08.200
in similar ideological battles.

00:05:08.200 --> 00:05:10.760
Battles that became
literal ones when Cuba began

00:05:10.760 --> 00:05:14.720
to send troops to Angola in 1975.

00:05:14.720 --> 00:05:19.840
A 1976 speech by Fidel Castro
commemorates the anniversaries

00:05:19.840 --> 00:05:25.190
of the Cuban victory over US
invaders in 1961 at Playa Giron,

00:05:25.190 --> 00:05:29.090
known in the US as the Bay of
Pigs, and Angola's independence

00:05:29.090 --> 00:05:33.230 position:56%
from Portugal, laying out the
rhetorical underpinnings of the long

00:05:33.230 --> 00:05:37.550
and tangled geo politics
links the two nations.

00:05:37.550 --> 00:05:41.770
In Giron, quote, in Giron,
African blood was spilled.

00:05:41.770 --> 00:05:45.340
That of the selfless
descendants of an enslaved people.

00:05:45.340 --> 00:05:49.310
And in Africa, together with
the heroic combatants of Angola,

00:05:49.310 --> 00:05:52.090
Cuban blood was also spilled.

00:05:52.090 --> 00:05:54.700
Those who one day enslaved
men and send them

00:05:54.700 --> 00:05:58.960
to America perhaps never
imagined that one of those nations

00:05:58.960 --> 00:06:01.990
that received slaves
would send its combatants

00:06:01.990 --> 00:06:04.510
to fight for liberty in Africa.

00:06:04.510 --> 00:06:08.690
The victory of Angola was the twin
sister of the victory at Giron.

00:06:08.690 --> 00:06:10.830
End quote.

00:06:10.830 --> 00:06:14.880
Angolan and other Luzo-African
intellectuals shared Castro's

00:06:14.880 --> 00:06:18.870
rhetoric of placing together two
moments of national revolution

00:06:18.870 --> 00:06:23.100
against colonial and neo-colonial
forces, as parallel events

00:06:23.100 --> 00:06:27.440
in a worldwide fight against
colonialism and imperialism.

00:06:27.440 --> 00:06:31.220
10 years prior, at the first
Tri- Continental Congress,

00:06:31.220 --> 00:06:34.450
that took place in Havana in 1966,

00:06:34.450 --> 00:06:38.350
Pisau Guinean revolutionary Amielka
Cabral [assumed spelling] had used

00:06:38.350 --> 00:06:41.550
almost the same language as
Castro, of retracing the roots

00:06:41.550 --> 00:06:45.620
of the slave trade in the shared
interest of decolonization.

00:06:45.620 --> 00:06:49.830 position:56%
In his speech, after lauding the
accomplishments of the Cuban miracle

00:06:49.830 --> 00:06:55.270
of the early revolutionary years,
he declares, quote, we are prepared

00:06:55.270 --> 00:06:59.280 position:56%
to send to Cuba as many men and
women as may be needed to compensate

00:06:59.280 --> 00:07:02.830
for the departure of those who
have interests or attitudes

00:07:02.830 --> 00:07:06.730
that are incompatible with the
interests of the Cuban people.

00:07:06.730 --> 00:07:11.260
Taking once again the formerly hard
and tragic path of our ancestors,

00:07:11.260 --> 00:07:15.520
mainly from Guinea and Angola,
who were taken to Cuba as slaves,

00:07:15.520 --> 00:07:19.470
we would come now as free men, to
strengthen the bonds of history,

00:07:19.470 --> 00:07:23.860
blood, and culture which unite
our peoples with the Cuban people.

00:07:23.860 --> 00:07:25.490
End quote.

00:07:25.490 --> 00:07:29.480
Angola was the site of Cuba's
largest internationalist military

00:07:29.480 --> 00:07:31.690
and humanitarian mission.

00:07:31.690 --> 00:07:34.840
During the first 15 years
of Angola's civil war,

00:07:34.840 --> 00:07:39.230
which lasted until 2002,
Cuba also sponsored thousands

00:07:39.230 --> 00:07:43.200
of African students on the island,
and send teacher, engineers,

00:07:43.200 --> 00:07:46.490
and doctors to Angola to
fill the technical voids left

00:07:46.490 --> 00:07:49.690
when Portuguese personnel
abandoned the country.

00:07:49.690 --> 00:07:51.190
Angola's politicians

00:07:51.190 --> 00:07:54.340
and intellectuals expressed
their gratitude publicly,

00:07:54.340 --> 00:07:56.670
and the two writers'
unions signed an agreement

00:07:56.670 --> 00:08:00.320
of mutual publication in 1976.

00:08:00.320 --> 00:08:03.900
The public rhetoric in national
and international publishing venues

00:08:03.900 --> 00:08:08.960
around South Atlantic emphasized a
process of mutual self-recognition,

00:08:08.960 --> 00:08:12.380
articulated, as we see in those
two speeches, through notions

00:08:12.380 --> 00:08:15.030
of Africa diasporic sibling-hood,

00:08:15.030 --> 00:08:19.050
as well as through
anti-imperialist solidarity.

00:08:19.050 --> 00:08:22.840
However, as much as this
period produced similar works

00:08:22.840 --> 00:08:27.500
of revolutionary solidarity, there
is a parallel stream in literature

00:08:27.500 --> 00:08:31.530
in both hemispheres that derails
the utopian imagined futures

00:08:31.530 --> 00:08:35.710
that develops among tightening
political and cultural policies,

00:08:35.710 --> 00:08:39.440
the death and mutilation of
thousands of soldiers in Africa,

00:08:39.440 --> 00:08:43.390
and the increasing distance
between political posturing

00:08:43.390 --> 00:08:48.390
and social disintegration as the
civil war escalated in Angola.

00:08:48.390 --> 00:08:51.040
This presentation will
discuss characteristics

00:08:51.040 --> 00:08:54.100
of this alternative phase of
Cuban and Angolan narratives

00:08:54.100 --> 00:08:56.290
from the late 20th century,

00:08:56.290 --> 00:09:01.440
analyzing Angolan author
Pepetela's 2001 novel Jaime Bunda,

00:09:01.440 --> 00:09:08.000
Secret Agent, and Cuban Eliseo
Alberto's 1998 novel Caracol Beach,

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:12.010 position:56%
through the lens of what I'm
calling a poetics of disappointment.

00:09:12.010 --> 00:09:15.510
I define disappointment as an
effective and formal response

00:09:15.510 --> 00:09:18.780
to revolutionary enthusiasm.

00:09:18.780 --> 00:09:22.400
In his article titled
Anatomy of Enthusiasm,

00:09:22.400 --> 00:09:26.770
Cuban historian Rafael Rojas
argues that the early years

00:09:26.770 --> 00:09:30.690
of the revolution represented
a spectacle of ideas,

00:09:30.690 --> 00:09:34.080
in which public debates
centered on the shape and future

00:09:34.080 --> 00:09:37.700
of the new utopian
revolutionary era.

00:09:37.700 --> 00:09:40.320
To describe the newness
of the feeling associated

00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:42.800
with this spectacle, Rojas draws

00:09:42.800 --> 00:09:48.470
on French theorist Jean Francois
Leotard's 1986 essay Enthusiasm:

00:09:48.470 --> 00:09:50.870
A Kantian Critique of History.

00:09:50.870 --> 00:09:54.710
In which Leotard proposes
an analogic relationship

00:09:54.710 --> 00:09:58.530
between an experience with
unprecedented political events,

00:09:58.530 --> 00:10:03.890
like revolution, and the Kantian
experience with the sublime.

00:10:03.890 --> 00:10:09.100
In Leotard's analysis, enthusiasm
offers a glimpse of the potential

00:10:09.100 --> 00:10:12.280
for social betterment that
provokes the observers

00:10:12.280 --> 00:10:16.790
of the revolutionary event
into a political commitment.

00:10:16.790 --> 00:10:19.560
While for Kant, the
French revolution serves

00:10:19.560 --> 00:10:21.860
as the foundational
event in modernity

00:10:21.860 --> 00:10:26.180
that inspires this feeling,
Leotard argues that different times

00:10:26.180 --> 00:10:29.460
and social conditions will
produce different events

00:10:29.460 --> 00:10:31.910
that produce widespread enthusiasm.

00:10:31.910 --> 00:10:36.170
He uses as his example
May of 1968 in Europe,

00:10:36.170 --> 00:10:38.640
while Rojas offers
the Cuban revolution

00:10:38.640 --> 00:10:41.360
as another possible event.

00:10:41.360 --> 00:10:44.080
This feeling of enthusiasm
for the possibility

00:10:44.080 --> 00:10:48.160 position:56%
of a more radically just society
produced particular types of culture

00:10:48.160 --> 00:10:50.660
on both sides of the Atlantic.

00:10:50.660 --> 00:10:55.570 position:56%
Angolan and Cuban literature and
film focus, for example, on revising

00:10:55.570 --> 00:10:57.750
or correcting the
Colonially-inflected

00:10:57.750 --> 00:10:59.450
historical record.

00:10:59.450 --> 00:11:02.440
On privileging subaltern
points of view.

00:11:02.440 --> 00:11:06.170
And on placing history and art
making into the metaphorical

00:11:06.170 --> 00:11:08.840
and literal hands of the masses.

00:11:08.840 --> 00:11:13.680
Artistic styles were concerned with
the new, with breaking past molds,

00:11:13.680 --> 00:11:18.590
in order to find a new visual and
verbal language, forms and styles

00:11:18.590 --> 00:11:23.300
that would adequately reflect
the new social conditions.

00:11:23.300 --> 00:11:28.020
The Cuban revolution in the 1960s,
therefore, had at least two,

00:11:28.020 --> 00:11:32.030
certainly more than two,
possible intellectual narratives.

00:11:32.030 --> 00:11:37.110
One as the inheritor of the
liberal tradition founded in 1789,

00:11:37.110 --> 00:11:40.840 position:56%
but a second one that privileged its
links to the anti-Colonial struggles

00:11:40.840 --> 00:11:44.100
across Latin America,
Africa and Asia.

00:11:44.100 --> 00:11:46.630
The second history is
theorized thoroughly

00:11:46.630 --> 00:11:53.040
in Cuban essayist Roberto Fernandez
Retamar's seminal essay Caliban,

00:11:53.040 --> 00:11:55.220
published in 1971.

00:11:55.220 --> 00:11:58.610
Which Rojas reads as a pivot
away from the possibilities

00:11:58.610 --> 00:12:03.150
of the liberal tradition toward
an ideology of third-worldism,

00:12:03.150 --> 00:12:06.790
in the essay's argument for using
the figure of Shakespeare's slave

00:12:06.790 --> 00:12:10.470
in the Tempest for a symbol
for Cuba's identification with

00:12:10.470 --> 00:12:14.310
and allegiance for the
formerly colonized world.

00:12:14.310 --> 00:12:17.930
Cuba's turn away from the
global North to embrace African

00:12:17.930 --> 00:12:19.950
and Latin American
liberation movements

00:12:19.950 --> 00:12:24.330
in the late 1960s precipitates,
among some of its theorists,

00:12:24.330 --> 00:12:26.820
a new genealogy of revolution.

00:12:26.820 --> 00:12:31.070 position:56%
Founded in a radically anti-Colonial
interpretation of the enslaved

00:12:31.070 --> 00:12:35.060
and the oppressed taking charge
of their historical future.

00:12:35.060 --> 00:12:38.370
It's no accident, for example,
that the Haitian revolution

00:12:38.370 --> 00:12:42.010
and its leadership appear in
literary and historical works

00:12:42.010 --> 00:12:44.670
as an alternate sign of
the age of revolutions,

00:12:44.670 --> 00:12:46.920
in novels and works of history.

00:12:46.920 --> 00:12:51.050 position:56%
And works discussing slavery focus
on acts of rebellion and resistance,

00:12:51.050 --> 00:12:54.290
rather than romantic
depictions of suffering.

00:12:54.290 --> 00:12:55.590
To Saint Lobeteur [assumed
spelling],

00:12:55.590 --> 00:12:58.690
among other black revolutionary
historical figures

00:12:58.690 --> 00:13:01.240
like the Brazilian Zumbidos
Palmaris [assumed spelling]

00:13:01.240 --> 00:13:04.620
and the Angolan Queen Inzinga
[assumed spelling] appear

00:13:04.620 --> 00:13:08.400 position:56%
in Angolan literature as
historical predecessors and founders

00:13:08.400 --> 00:13:11.610
of a tradition of resistance.

00:13:11.610 --> 00:13:15.220
However, a series of events,
starting in the late 1960s

00:13:15.220 --> 00:13:17.620
and continuing into the 1970s,

00:13:17.620 --> 00:13:20.630
altered the artistic
and political landscape.

00:13:20.630 --> 00:13:24.530
Precipitating Cuba's break
with the Euro-American left.

00:13:24.530 --> 00:13:26.540 position:56%
On the Cuban side, first, the series

00:13:26.540 --> 00:13:31.200
of high profile censorship
cases in the late 1960s.

00:13:31.200 --> 00:13:34.140
Especially the imprisonment
and forced confession of crimes

00:13:34.140 --> 00:13:38.830
against the revolution by
poet Heberto Padilla in 1971,

00:13:38.830 --> 00:13:45.010
and the silencing of playwright
Anton Arrufat after 1968.

00:13:45.010 --> 00:13:48.520
Second, the establishment of
the Cuban Cultural Ministry

00:13:48.520 --> 00:13:52.780
to centrally regulate cultural
production, initiating the period

00:13:52.780 --> 00:13:56.730
that essayist Ambrosio Fornet
calls the gray five years

00:13:56.730 --> 00:14:00.670
in the early 1970s, for
its top-down implementation

00:14:00.670 --> 00:14:04.880
of strict esthetic models and
the threat of ostracization,

00:14:04.880 --> 00:14:09.050
imprisonment or censure for
those who did not comply.

00:14:09.050 --> 00:14:13.040
In Angola, after the leftist
MPLA party won the government

00:14:13.040 --> 00:14:15.800
in the months after
independence from Portugal,

00:14:15.800 --> 00:14:20.040 position:56%
the anti-colonial conflict escalated
into an international conflict,

00:14:20.040 --> 00:14:23.210
when South Africa invaded
its southern borders.

00:14:23.210 --> 00:14:26.520
And then progressed to
a full-out civil war.

00:14:26.520 --> 00:14:30.710
1977's failed coup
d'etat, led by Nito Alves

00:14:30.710 --> 00:14:34.630
against then-president Agostinho
Neto, resulted in series

00:14:34.630 --> 00:14:38.190
of forced confessions,
persecution and execution

00:14:38.190 --> 00:14:39.950
of presumed collaborators.

00:14:39.950 --> 00:14:43.340
And the civil conflict
continued to intensify.

00:14:43.340 --> 00:14:44.640
It was accompanied

00:14:44.640 --> 00:14:47.470
by a State-sponsored publishing
program similar to Cuba's,

00:14:47.470 --> 00:14:51.490
where literature proliferated, but
where the political thrust of works

00:14:51.490 --> 00:14:54.970
of art were tightly monitored,
to be sure of compliance

00:14:54.970 --> 00:14:58.940
with the program linked
to revolutionary ideals.

00:14:58.940 --> 00:15:02.270
This period, in short,
ushered in the beginners

00:15:02.270 --> 00:15:05.530
of a widespread feeling
of disappointment.

00:15:05.530 --> 00:15:10.790
In my work, disappointment responds
to how the radical possibilities

00:15:10.790 --> 00:15:14.980
of revolutionary promise take
on recognizable political forms,

00:15:14.980 --> 00:15:18.720
such as bureaucratization,
censorship and corruption,

00:15:18.720 --> 00:15:21.450
while the new literary forms
that had been associated

00:15:21.450 --> 00:15:22.980
with utopian ideals

00:15:22.980 --> 00:15:25.500
and revolutionary promise
become the basis

00:15:25.500 --> 00:15:28.400
for prescribed esthetic models.

00:15:28.400 --> 00:15:33.080
Texts of disappointment revisit the
radical possibilities of revolution

00:15:33.080 --> 00:15:35.800
through a poetics of
citation and imitation.

00:15:35.800 --> 00:15:40.900 position:56%
They used techniques such as parody,
pastiche and historical re-writing.

00:15:40.900 --> 00:15:45.630
These practices, in turn,
interrogate the meaning of signs,

00:15:45.630 --> 00:15:49.320
forms or events for which the
cultural value is changing.

00:15:49.320 --> 00:15:53.820
So, I'm now going to
turn to the first example

00:15:53.820 --> 00:15:56.270
of a literary text
of disappointment.

00:15:56.270 --> 00:15:59.000
The satirical detective
novel Jaime Bunda,

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:01.040
Secret Agent, by Angolan novelist

00:16:01.040 --> 00:16:05.490
Ahtur Carlos Mauricio
Pestano du Santus,

00:16:05.490 --> 00:16:08.710
better known by his
pen name of Pepetela.

00:16:08.710 --> 00:16:11.750
Perhaps the most famed
living Angolan writer,

00:16:11.750 --> 00:16:15.720
Pepetela's corpus spans the early
years of revolutionary action

00:16:15.720 --> 00:16:19.120 position:56%
in the mid-1970s to the present day.

00:16:19.120 --> 00:16:22.760
In the midst of a career of
prize-winning historical novels

00:16:22.760 --> 00:16:26.920
and later works critical of the
corruption and domestic conflict,

00:16:26.920 --> 00:16:29.770
Pepetela has written
two Jaime Bunda novels.

00:16:29.770 --> 00:16:33.960 position:56%
Jaime Bunda, Secret Agent, published
in 2001, and the follow-up,

00:16:33.960 --> 00:16:39.000
Jaime Bunda and the dead of the
American, published in 2003.

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:42.440
They appear in the decade after
the constitutional reforms

00:16:42.440 --> 00:16:47.070
of 1991 left behind the single
party government in favor

00:16:47.070 --> 00:16:50.020
of a Capitalist, multi-party
democracy.

00:16:50.020 --> 00:16:51.820
In Pepetela's depiction,

00:16:51.820 --> 00:16:56.260
turned kleptocratic
autocracy in the 21st century.

00:16:56.260 --> 00:17:00.030
The protagonist of both novels
is the comically inept secret

00:17:00.030 --> 00:17:03.380
not-so-secret agent of
Angola's fictional general

00:17:03.380 --> 00:17:04.940
investigative service.

00:17:04.940 --> 00:17:10.140
He obtains his nickname, Abunda,
due to his outsize back side,

00:17:10.140 --> 00:17:12.570
which is what Bunda
means in Portuguese.

00:17:12.570 --> 00:17:15.270
He holds his lowly
junior position only due

00:17:15.270 --> 00:17:18.550
to the nepotism of
a distant relative.

00:17:18.550 --> 00:17:22.330
While both the Jaime Bunda novels
nod to the genre conventions

00:17:22.330 --> 00:17:26.980 position:56%
of detective fiction, in both novels
he's attempting to solve a murder.

00:17:26.980 --> 00:17:30.350
The wandering, tangled intrigue
of government corruption,

00:17:30.350 --> 00:17:33.870
social disorganization,
false leads, misinformation,

00:17:33.870 --> 00:17:38.910
and widespread ineptitude, by the
end of both novels, fails to result

00:17:38.910 --> 00:17:42.990
in a satisfactory resolution
for either crime.

00:17:42.990 --> 00:17:46.210
In Jaime Bunda, Secret
Agent, the titular character,

00:17:46.210 --> 00:17:49.030
the laughing stock of his
office, gets his big break

00:17:49.030 --> 00:17:51.960
when his boss recruits him
to oversee the investigation

00:17:51.960 --> 00:17:54.970
of the rape and murder
of a teenage girl.

00:17:54.970 --> 00:17:58.870 position:56%
Jaime finds it strange to devote
national police efforts to the case,

00:17:58.870 --> 00:18:02.720
since her family is neither
politically nor socially prominent.

00:18:02.720 --> 00:18:04.500
But it is his first chance to put

00:18:04.500 --> 00:18:07.420
into practice the investigative
techniques he has read

00:18:07.420 --> 00:18:12.450
about in the English language crime
novels and films that he favors.

00:18:12.450 --> 00:18:15.480
He ultimately fails to discover
that the murderer is the son

00:18:15.480 --> 00:18:17.170
of a prominent Congress member.

00:18:17.170 --> 00:18:20.050
That crime is solved
by the local police.

00:18:20.050 --> 00:18:24.750
But he does accidentally stumble
upon an international counterfeit

00:18:24.750 --> 00:18:26.490
currency ring.

00:18:26.490 --> 00:18:28.980
His discovery leads to the
apprehension of several

00:18:28.980 --> 00:18:32.210
of the players, but leaves
the masterminds at large.

00:18:32.210 --> 00:18:35.800
Nonetheless, Jaime distracted
from his original mission,

00:18:35.800 --> 00:18:39.740
and more concerned with his esteem
in his office, and his access

00:18:39.740 --> 00:18:44.270
to a gun and a car, accepts
his new reputation as a star,

00:18:44.270 --> 00:18:47.260
more or less willing to accede
to the version of the truth

00:18:47.260 --> 00:18:50.970
that puts him and his collaborators
in favor with the bosses.

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:54.320
In the novel's portrayal
of this inept

00:18:54.320 --> 00:18:56.990
but accidentally successful
investigator,

00:18:56.990 --> 00:19:01.020
we can read in Pepetela a satire
of a wide variety of aspects

00:19:01.020 --> 00:19:03.440
of contemporary Angolan society.

00:19:03.440 --> 00:19:06.030 position:56%
Including nepotism and his critiques

00:19:06.030 --> 00:19:09.780
of a rising revolutionary
elite turned bourgeoisie

00:19:09.780 --> 00:19:11.480
in the 21st century.

00:19:11.480 --> 00:19:14.230
Who, following the post-
Cold War political winds,

00:19:14.230 --> 00:19:16.590
embrace all things American.

00:19:16.590 --> 00:19:19.480
Although, of course, a
running joke in the novel is

00:19:19.480 --> 00:19:22.730
that Jaime can't distinguish
references to British detectives

00:19:22.730 --> 00:19:27.580
like Sherlock Holmes, J.G. Reeder
and James Bond from American ones

00:19:27.580 --> 00:19:31.410
like Mike Hammer, Philip
Marlow and Perry Mason.

00:19:31.410 --> 00:19:35.070
For him, they're all gringos.

00:19:35.070 --> 00:19:37.180
However, in the connections
between the way

00:19:37.180 --> 00:19:41.060
that the novel narrates Jaime's
imitation of fictional detectives,

00:19:41.060 --> 00:19:44.890
I also read the novel as a
literary pastiche, and here,

00:19:44.890 --> 00:19:49.200 position:56%
I'm drawing on Jeanette's definition
of pastiche as a satirical form

00:19:49.200 --> 00:19:54.030
of imitation that is
primarily concerned with style.

00:19:54.030 --> 00:19:58.440
Pepetela manifests the stylistic
imitation central to pastiche

00:19:58.440 --> 00:20:02.040
in describing Jaime Bunda's
approach to investigation.

00:20:02.040 --> 00:20:05.360
Drawn from a literary
history of careful observation

00:20:05.360 --> 00:20:08.940
and logical deduction,
clearly rooted in classics

00:20:08.940 --> 00:20:12.190
like Edgar Allen Poe
and Conan Doyle.

00:20:12.190 --> 00:20:14.200
The first time we meet Jaime,

00:20:14.200 --> 00:20:16.830
we learned that while he lacks
the confidence of his bosses

00:20:16.830 --> 00:20:20.760
and co-workers, he has honed
his observational acumen

00:20:20.760 --> 00:20:23.810
through minute observation
of the details around him.

00:20:23.810 --> 00:20:27.630
Quote, they never gave him a chance
to prove that he could be an ace,

00:20:27.630 --> 00:20:30.580
only ordering him to
go and buy cigarettes.

00:20:30.580 --> 00:20:34.010
