00:29:28.540 --> 00:29:31.850
is Cuban novelist Eliseo
Alberto's Caracol Beach.

00:29:31.850 --> 00:29:34.590
But I want to begin, however,
with a discussion of an image,

00:29:34.590 --> 00:29:36.470
to which I'll return
at the end of the talk.

00:29:36.470 --> 00:29:38.940
And special thanks to Aroun Soud
[assumed spelling] for the image.

00:29:38.940 --> 00:29:44.980
Ah. This is missing
a -- there we go.

00:29:44.980 --> 00:29:48.150
Okay.

00:29:48.150 --> 00:29:52.230 position:56%
Popular knowledge asserts that
Fidel Castro never appeared publicly

00:29:52.230 --> 00:29:57.910
in anything other than military
fatigues between 1959 and 1994,

00:29:57.910 --> 00:30:01.150
when he was famously
photographed in a guayabera.

00:30:01.150 --> 00:30:04.860
His fatigues continued to be
Fidel's preferred public dress,

00:30:04.860 --> 00:30:09.040
until he stepped down from
the presidency in 2006.

00:30:09.040 --> 00:30:13.240
In the days after his death, the
state newspaper Granma ran photos

00:30:13.240 --> 00:30:16.250
of Fidel from throughout
his long political life.

00:30:16.250 --> 00:30:19.880
Chatting with peasants and
schoolchildren, playing baseball,

00:30:19.880 --> 00:30:24.010 position:56%
greeting world leaders, and speaking
from podiums, all the while dressed

00:30:24.010 --> 00:30:27.670
in the military uniform that
provided him visual continuity

00:30:27.670 --> 00:30:30.110
over the decades of his influence.

00:30:30.110 --> 00:30:35.440
The cover page graphic from
the November 27 issue, a black

00:30:35.440 --> 00:30:40.020
and white stylized image of
dozens of identical armed Fidels,

00:30:40.020 --> 00:30:43.820
emphasizes both the saturation
of images of the iconic leader,

00:30:43.820 --> 00:30:48.430 position:56%
and communicates the idea of the
soldier cum everyman in the headline

00:30:48.430 --> 00:30:50.280
that accompanies the image.

00:30:50.280 --> 00:30:52.870
Cuba is Fidel.

00:30:52.870 --> 00:30:55.620
Depending on the viewer's
visual, rhetorical

00:30:55.620 --> 00:30:59.480
or political vantage point, the
graphics suggest an audience

00:30:59.480 --> 00:31:02.150
which is incorporated
into the multitude,

00:31:02.150 --> 00:31:05.960
replicating Fidel's march toward
the future of the revolution.

00:31:05.960 --> 00:31:08.620
Or, alternately, viewers
faced with an army

00:31:08.620 --> 00:31:11.700
of infinitely reproducing
opposing forces,

00:31:11.700 --> 00:31:14.790
perhaps even about to be overcome.

00:31:14.790 --> 00:31:17.450
The starkly divisive
implications of the black

00:31:17.450 --> 00:31:21.050
and white graphic encapsulate
one of the ways in which authors

00:31:21.050 --> 00:31:23.390
such as Eliseo Alberto reflect

00:31:23.390 --> 00:31:26.300
on the revolution's
rhetorical inheritances,

00:31:26.300 --> 00:31:29.450
where the neat partitions
of the Cuban community seem

00:31:29.450 --> 00:31:31.830
to themselves divide and multiply,

00:31:31.830 --> 00:31:35.530
producing dozens of
different iterations.

00:31:35.530 --> 00:31:38.130
We'll come back to this image.

00:31:38.130 --> 00:31:43.670
Eliseo Alberto's 1998 novel Caracol
Beach explores the profound impacts

00:31:43.670 --> 00:31:48.790
of what the author sees as a Cuban
community divided against itself.

00:31:48.790 --> 00:31:53.520
The Cuban revolution's saturation
of images, slogans and language

00:31:53.520 --> 00:31:57.860
of militarization and Manichean
divides is one of the effects

00:31:57.860 --> 00:32:01.720
of a national leadership that saw
itself as under constant threat,

00:32:01.720 --> 00:32:05.260
or even attack, by larger
forces of imperialism,

00:32:05.260 --> 00:32:08.460
usually the United States, that
threatened to undo the course

00:32:08.460 --> 00:32:11.120
of its history since 1959.

00:32:11.120 --> 00:32:14.160 position:56%
Or even to annihilate it altogether.

00:32:14.160 --> 00:32:18.200
Alberto's novel addresses the
extension of the sense of threat

00:32:18.200 --> 00:32:21.040
from without through
reference to two phenomena

00:32:21.040 --> 00:32:23.620
that mark the configuration
of the Cuban community

00:32:23.620 --> 00:32:26.070
in the latter decades
of the 20th century.

00:32:26.070 --> 00:32:29.740
The internationalist missions
abroad, ostensibly extensions

00:32:29.740 --> 00:32:33.720
of revolutionary fervor and
solidarity on foreign ground,

00:32:33.720 --> 00:32:36.200
and the divisions among
the Cuban community,

00:32:36.200 --> 00:32:38.730 position:56%
especially as imposed through exile.

00:32:38.730 --> 00:32:46.180
In Caracol Beach, the protagonist,
Beto Milanes, a Cuban soldier

00:32:46.180 --> 00:32:48.790
in the Angolan war,
is the sole survivor

00:32:48.790 --> 00:32:51.320
after his company is ambushed.

00:32:51.320 --> 00:32:54.400
Convinced that he has betrayed
his country after he's rescued

00:32:54.400 --> 00:33:00.000
by American forces, Beto chooses
17 years of isolation and exile

00:33:00.000 --> 00:33:04.490
over facing what he is sure
will be punishment back in Cuba.

00:33:04.490 --> 00:33:09.070
Beto sees suicide as the only
way to rid himself of the madness

00:33:09.070 --> 00:33:10.940
that haunts him after the war,

00:33:10.940 --> 00:33:14.680
symbolized in a winged tiger
that follows him around.

00:33:14.680 --> 00:33:18.490
He kidnaps three teenagers to
assist him in his death wish,

00:33:18.490 --> 00:33:21.430
forcing two of them to commit
increasingly violent acts

00:33:21.430 --> 00:33:25.450
against strangers, and
ultimately these two die with him

00:33:25.450 --> 00:33:29.210
in absurd accidents at
the end of the novel.

00:33:29.210 --> 00:33:32.970
So, my argument here is that this
novel critiques the reproduction

00:33:32.970 --> 00:33:37.430
of violence, focusing on how
media images of Cuba at war result

00:33:37.430 --> 00:33:41.830
in a system that passes real
violence along a chain of actors.

00:33:41.830 --> 00:33:43.810
Including the violence
of a community divided

00:33:43.810 --> 00:33:46.130
between the island and exile.

00:33:46.130 --> 00:33:47.780
Beyond its critique, however,

00:33:47.780 --> 00:33:51.060
Alberto's novel also
calls for a kind of truce.

00:33:51.060 --> 00:33:54.150
Looking to Afro-Cuban
ritual as a counterpoint

00:33:54.150 --> 00:33:55.960
to bring the many divided factions

00:33:55.960 --> 00:33:59.040
of the Cuban community
toward reconciliation.

00:33:59.040 --> 00:34:04.620
Eliseo Albert de Diego Garcia
Marruz, another long name,

00:34:04.620 --> 00:34:07.400
is part of one of the most
prominent intellectual families

00:34:07.400 --> 00:34:12.020
of 20th century Cuba, and was
an eclectic and prolific writer.

00:34:12.020 --> 00:34:14.610
He established his
reputation in journalism,

00:34:14.610 --> 00:34:17.490
film and eventually
television script writing,

00:34:17.490 --> 00:34:21.360
and published chronicles,
essays, poetry and novels.

00:34:21.360 --> 00:34:27.750
He moved to Mexico in 1988, and
despite many attempts to return,

00:34:27.750 --> 00:34:32.940
was only able to return to Cuba
in 2010, a year before he died.

00:34:32.940 --> 00:34:34.240
The breadth of his area

00:34:34.240 --> 00:34:37.830
of production are evident
particularly in his novels.

00:34:37.830 --> 00:34:41.040
In addition to a vast array of
cultural reference points drawn

00:34:41.040 --> 00:34:45.310
from music, literature and film,
Caracol Beach frequently lapses

00:34:45.310 --> 00:34:49.000
into extradiagetic
commentary that reads at times

00:34:49.000 --> 00:34:53.330 position:56%
like a film voiceover, stage
directions, or director's commentary

00:34:53.330 --> 00:34:55.900
on the action taking
place in the background.

00:34:55.900 --> 00:35:00.000
Beyond a quirk of the individual
author's range of talents

00:35:00.000 --> 00:35:01.670
and interests, however, I think

00:35:01.670 --> 00:35:04.870
that this technique points
to a broader context.

00:35:04.870 --> 00:35:07.820
Alberto was a young child
when the revolution triumphed,

00:35:07.820 --> 00:35:09.210
and was educated and came

00:35:09.210 --> 00:35:12.900
of age during its first
two turbulent decades.

00:35:12.900 --> 00:35:16.060
The cinematic texture of
the novel thus also signals

00:35:16.060 --> 00:35:20.480
to its readers a history of the
ongoing participatory construction

00:35:20.480 --> 00:35:26.310 position:56%
of the revolution and its lived
realities via visual representation.

00:35:26.310 --> 00:35:29.800
Critic Lillian Guerra has analyzed
the revolution's construction

00:35:29.800 --> 00:35:34.220
in media via what she
called a hyperreal futurity.

00:35:34.220 --> 00:35:37.670
She focuses on television,
photography and films portrayal

00:35:37.670 --> 00:35:40.850
of social mechanisms,
like mass rallies,

00:35:40.850 --> 00:35:44.350
voluntary labor, and
military service.

00:35:44.350 --> 00:35:48.280
In post-modern theory and media
studies, the hyperreal refers

00:35:48.280 --> 00:35:52.150
to a displacement or
disappearance of external reality,

00:35:52.150 --> 00:35:55.970
in favor of a reality
experienced through simulation,

00:35:55.970 --> 00:35:58.650
image and representation.

00:35:58.650 --> 00:36:00.510
Guerra explains.

00:36:00.510 --> 00:36:03.530
Critical to explaining the
imagery's importance to struggles

00:36:03.530 --> 00:36:07.100
over the grand narrative
is the idea that images --

00:36:07.100 --> 00:36:10.080 position:56%
photographic, imaginary, personal --

00:36:10.080 --> 00:36:13.800
played a central role in placing
Cubans outside the mundane

00:36:13.800 --> 00:36:15.360
circumstances of their daily lives,

00:36:15.360 --> 00:36:18.890
and into the hyperreality
of the revolution.

00:36:18.890 --> 00:36:23.350
That is, a utopia caught
in the process of becoming.

00:36:23.350 --> 00:36:27.030
Like hyperreal spaces in
any society, hyperrealities

00:36:27.030 --> 00:36:29.240
of State-orchestrated mass rallies

00:36:29.240 --> 00:36:33.440
and routinized volunteer labor
projects convinced participants

00:36:33.440 --> 00:36:37.280
that the euphoria, the
happiness, the sense of justice,

00:36:37.280 --> 00:36:39.300
the pride of unity and
self-righteousness,

00:36:39.300 --> 00:36:44.190
that the experience generated,
were emblematic of reality.

00:36:44.190 --> 00:36:46.850
That is, the rest of
the society external

00:36:46.850 --> 00:36:49.260
to the hyperreal experience.

00:36:49.260 --> 00:36:53.600
One authenticated the other, even
though they were not the same.

00:36:53.600 --> 00:36:55.840
That authentication
showed that the values

00:36:55.840 --> 00:36:59.950
of the hyperreal experience
should not be contested.

00:36:59.950 --> 00:37:01.250
End quote.

00:37:01.250 --> 00:37:06.970
In Caracol Beach, the vestiges of
the revolutionary hyperreality show

00:37:06.970 --> 00:37:10.210
up most frequently in the
soldier's flashbacks and memories

00:37:10.210 --> 00:37:12.130
of his experience in Angola.

00:37:12.130 --> 00:37:16.840
But lose their integration
with his present reality.

00:37:16.840 --> 00:37:19.310
In the novel's present,
the soldier's kidnapping

00:37:19.310 --> 00:37:23.580
of the teenagers holding one
named Laura hostage calls

00:37:23.580 --> 00:37:26.410
up the familiar Hollywood
cinematic plot convention

00:37:26.410 --> 00:37:27.870
of the woman in peril.

00:37:27.870 --> 00:37:31.520
Perhaps even a direct reference,
a possibility that just occurred

00:37:31.520 --> 00:37:36.630
to me a few weeks ago, to the
classic 1944 noir film Laura,

00:37:36.630 --> 00:37:40.240
who many of us saw together.

00:37:40.240 --> 00:37:42.930
However, the predominating
references are

00:37:42.930 --> 00:37:45.430
to the genre of war ethic.

00:37:45.430 --> 00:37:48.560
Connected explicitly
to the war in Angola.

00:37:48.560 --> 00:37:52.210
The surprise ambush that kills
Beto's fellow soldiers is a kind

00:37:52.210 --> 00:37:56.580
of twisted, negative incarnation of
the war films that Beto is trained

00:37:56.580 --> 00:37:58.990
with in advance of his deployment.

00:37:58.990 --> 00:38:02.100 position:56%
Specifically, Soviet war propaganda.

00:38:02.100 --> 00:38:05.550
While his disillusionment and
even madness caused by the loss

00:38:05.550 --> 00:38:08.350
of his companions and his
homeland are foreshadowed

00:38:08.350 --> 00:38:13.260
in his frequent references to
Akira Kurasawa's Seven Samurai.

00:38:13.260 --> 00:38:15.120
While I won't have
time today to analyze

00:38:15.120 --> 00:38:17.850
in detail the specific film
references in the novel,

00:38:17.850 --> 00:38:20.350
I do want to examine
the place in the novel

00:38:20.350 --> 00:38:23.410
of media representation
of violence in general.

00:38:23.410 --> 00:38:27.080
The difference between
cinematic scripting

00:38:27.080 --> 00:38:30.720
and the soldier's lived reality
remains the underlying conflict

00:38:30.720 --> 00:38:34.000
for the character's experience.

00:38:34.000 --> 00:38:38.120
As he recounts in his soldier's
diary, quote, what's happening is

00:38:38.120 --> 00:38:40.090
that nothing is happening.

00:38:40.090 --> 00:38:42.370
In training, back in Cuba,
they showed us movies

00:38:42.370 --> 00:38:46.400
about the Great Patriotic War, and
naturally the defense of Leningrad

00:38:46.400 --> 00:38:50.960
that lasted months and months was
condensed into two hours, in color,

00:38:50.960 --> 00:38:52.580
with music in the background.

00:38:52.580 --> 00:38:54.380
And so, the battles were exciting.

00:38:54.380 --> 00:38:57.470
But in real life, you will learn
that wars are full of dead time.

00:38:57.470 --> 00:38:59.710
Routine. The worse boredom.

00:38:59.710 --> 00:39:02.580
You dig trenches and fill
them in, climb a tree,

00:39:02.580 --> 00:39:05.870
get water from the river, and
you don't see shooting anywhere.

00:39:05.870 --> 00:39:09.180
Or you hear it like thunder in
a rainstorm falling in hell,

00:39:09.180 --> 00:39:11.420
until I guess the day
comes when it's your turn

00:39:11.420 --> 00:39:13.160
to get wet in a shower of lead.

00:39:13.160 --> 00:39:16.760
And others see our lightning in
the distance, while they're digging

00:39:16.760 --> 00:39:18.730
and filling their trenches.

00:39:18.730 --> 00:39:21.520
Poundcake says we really
are seven samurai.

00:39:21.520 --> 00:39:22.940
I'm the crazy one.

00:39:22.940 --> 00:39:26.390
Because just for a roof over
our head, and a few sardines,

00:39:26.390 --> 00:39:30.240
we've come to defend the future of
a people we've never even heard of.

00:39:30.240 --> 00:39:31.960
End quote.

00:39:31.960 --> 00:39:36.660
Betos' epithet of the crazy one,
which recurs throughout the novel,

00:39:36.660 --> 00:39:40.320
results in this case from
the gaps in his comprehension

00:39:40.320 --> 00:39:42.950
between experience and image.

00:39:42.950 --> 00:39:47.450 position:56%
What defies logic for him results in
searching for a state of perception

00:39:47.450 --> 00:39:52.050
that accommodates simultaneously
contradictory experience

00:39:52.050 --> 00:39:53.540
and representation.

00:39:53.540 --> 00:39:58.720
Guerra discusses the case of Cuban
documentary filmmaker Nicolas

00:39:58.720 --> 00:40:02.430 position:56%
Guillen Landrian [assumed spelling],
whose films throughout the 1960s

00:40:02.430 --> 00:40:06.040
and 1970s were repeatedly
censored by the State.

00:40:06.040 --> 00:40:10.090
While the film maker was forcibly
interned in a mental asylum.

00:40:10.090 --> 00:40:12.870
Authorities argue that
his films were, quote,

00:40:12.870 --> 00:40:15.180
incoherent with the context.

00:40:15.180 --> 00:40:16.520
End quote.

00:40:16.520 --> 00:40:21.210
Here, Guerra points to a critical
intersection between State power

00:40:21.210 --> 00:40:24.810
and the artist's power to create
the lived reality of the audience,

00:40:24.810 --> 00:40:28.090
via the hyperreal world of art.

00:40:28.090 --> 00:40:32.110 position:56%
Guerra's characterization of Guillen
Landrian casts the filmmaker's

00:40:32.110 --> 00:40:36.220
madness as a result of
the failure of the artist

00:40:36.220 --> 00:40:37.860
to accommodate the work of art

00:40:37.860 --> 00:40:41.250
to the idealized experience
of the people.

00:40:41.250 --> 00:40:44.710
Being out of coherence with
the context is equivalent

00:40:44.710 --> 00:40:47.810
to being out of one's mind.

00:40:47.810 --> 00:40:52.290
Beto's madness is certainly a
result of being out of context.

00:40:52.290 --> 00:40:55.250
He believes himself to be
a failed revolutionary.

00:40:55.250 --> 00:40:59.170
Since he survived the attack that
killed his entire fellow company.

00:40:59.170 --> 00:41:02.880
And is literally out of context
by living in exile in the land

00:41:02.880 --> 00:41:05.710
of the enemy, the United States.

00:41:05.710 --> 00:41:09.770
His solution, however, rather
than a challenge to State power,

00:41:09.770 --> 00:41:13.060
is to restore his proper
cinematic ending.

00:41:13.060 --> 00:41:17.110
By scripting his own death to
comply with the cinematic trope

00:41:17.110 --> 00:41:22.490
of the revolutionary soldier who
sacrifices himself to the cause.

00:41:22.490 --> 00:41:26.110
He describes the scene in
a letter to his rescuer.

00:41:26.110 --> 00:41:30.040
Quote. Watch for any carelessness
on my part and shoot me.

00:41:30.040 --> 00:41:31.470
Bring your son.

00:41:31.470 --> 00:41:34.800
The boy will witness a wonderful
scene, like in the movies.

00:41:34.800 --> 00:41:37.620
I'll fall on the sand,
in slow motion.

00:41:37.620 --> 00:41:38.920
Background music.

00:41:38.920 --> 00:41:40.220
A harmonica.

00:41:40.220 --> 00:41:42.690
The sand will gradually
turn red with blood.

00:41:42.690 --> 00:41:44.080
Don't turn my body over.

00:41:44.080 --> 00:41:46.860
Leave me like that, with
my arms out stretched.

00:41:46.860 --> 00:41:49.510
A fistful of sand in my right hand,

00:41:49.510 --> 00:41:53.320
the fingers of my right
hand spread open in a fan.

00:41:53.320 --> 00:41:55.130
Fabulous. Bring your son.

00:41:55.130 --> 00:41:57.090
End quote.

00:41:57.090 --> 00:41:58.390
So, this is a trope.

00:41:58.390 --> 00:42:03.230
Here, I just have three apologies
for the poor quality screenshots

00:42:03.230 --> 00:42:08.540
from Cuban films, roughly
contemporary to Alberto's career.

00:42:08.540 --> 00:42:12.110
Two of them, Caravanna and
Cangamba, are films about Angola.

00:42:12.110 --> 00:42:13.870
But this appears everywhere.

00:42:13.870 --> 00:42:15.610
You guys have all seen it.

00:42:15.610 --> 00:42:18.430
The details that the soldier
mentions, the background music,

00:42:18.430 --> 00:42:22.060
the slow spreading of the blood,
the position of the hands.

00:42:22.060 --> 00:42:23.360
Even the perspective

00:42:23.360 --> 00:42:27.660
of the spectators fulfill
the cinematic particulars

00:42:27.660 --> 00:42:30.060
that we're missing among
the tedium and the boredom

00:42:30.060 --> 00:42:33.000
of his dead time in real combat.

00:42:33.000 --> 00:42:37.310
They produce, via simulated image,
the sacrifice that would allow him

00:42:37.310 --> 00:42:41.430
to comply with the projected course
of the revolutionary soldier.

00:42:41.430 --> 00:42:45.580
But, more importantly, however,
their cinematic staging transmits

00:42:45.580 --> 00:42:49.310
that message of sacrifice
to the spectators.

00:42:49.310 --> 00:42:53.300
Those spectators he has built
into his own staging of the scene.

00:42:53.300 --> 00:42:55.390
Bring your son.

00:42:55.390 --> 00:42:59.780
The ultimate danger of the kind of
aestheticized and scripted violence

00:42:59.780 --> 00:43:04.200
that the soldier imagines is
not just his individual suicide.

00:43:04.200 --> 00:43:07.850
But the reproducibility, and
then the actual reproduction,

00:43:07.850 --> 00:43:11.250
of the violent scene,
resulting, Alberto warns,

00:43:11.250 --> 00:43:14.080
in a kind of collective
annihilation.

00:43:14.080 --> 00:43:18.100
The wartime violence also
serves, crucially in the novel,

00:43:18.100 --> 00:43:22.550
as a metaphor for the reproduction
of violence on the Cuban community.

00:43:22.550 --> 00:43:26.000
Politically motivated divisions
on the island and, of course,

00:43:26.000 --> 00:43:28.720
the fundamental violence of exile.

00:43:28.720 --> 00:43:32.010
Virtually the entire novel
takes place on foreign ground.

00:43:32.010 --> 00:43:34.550
Either Angola or Florida.

00:43:34.550 --> 00:43:38.530
The conflict between hyperreality
and lived experience culminate

00:43:38.530 --> 00:43:41.020
in Beto's final climactic
performance.

00:43:41.020 --> 00:43:42.940
His actual death.

00:43:42.940 --> 00:43:45.650
But one that does not comply
with the cinematic end

00:43:45.650 --> 00:43:47.740
that he's imagined for himself.

00:43:47.740 --> 00:43:52.630
It turns into, rather, a ritual
about space, where the damaged,

00:43:52.630 --> 00:43:56.640
the exiled, and the
mad can find release.

00:43:56.640 --> 00:44:00.860
In Beto's final act, expecting
to be shot by police officers

00:44:00.860 --> 00:44:03.130
